Amazon Sneaker Sales Analysis EDA Project
  1. Problem Definition

Ravi is a working professional planning to buy a pair of sneakers for daily use. He visits Amazon and searches for sneakers, only to find thousands of options with similar-looking designs but huge price differences.

Despite similar features like:

Material quality

Brand type

Customer ratings

Usage type (casual, running, sports)

He observes:

Some sneakers cost 999 1,499 Others cost 3,000 8,000+ This creates confusion for Ravi and millions of online shoppers.

  1. Business Problem Statement

Online sneaker buyers face difficulty in selecting the right product due to overwhelming choices and unclear pricing logic. The objective is to analyze Amazon sneaker data using Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to understand pricing patterns, feature impact, and value-for-money insights.

  1. Project Objectives

Brand Representation

Gender Distribution

Selling Price Distribution

Discount Percentage Distribution

Rating Category Distribution

Selling Price vs Discount Amount

Price Category vs Rating

Gender vs Usage Type

Brand vs Average Rating

Average Selling Price by Price Category

Selling Price Distribution by Price Category

Provide data-driven insights for smarter buying decisions

  1. Data Analytics Life Cycle

This project follows the standard Data Analytics Life Cycle:

  1. Business Problem & Business Understanding

Understand customer confusion around sneaker pricing Identify buyer expectations (quality vs price) Define key analytical questions for EDA

  1. Data Collection & Data Understanding

Scrape sneaker data from Amazon Collected attributes include: Product Name Brand Price (MRP / Discounted Price) Ratings Number of Reviews Sneaker Type (Casual, Running, Sports) Availability status Understand data types and structure

  1. Data Preprocessing (Cleaning)

Remove currency symbols (, commas) from price columns Handle missing values in ratings and reviews Convert text-based numeric columns into integers/floats Remove duplicate product listings Standardize brand names

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

Price distribution analysis Brand-wise price comparison Relationship between: Price vs Ratings Price vs Number of Reviews Identify premium vs budget segments Detect outliers and overpriced products Value-for-money analysis

Tools used:

Pandas

Matplotlib

Seaborn

  1. Conclusion

Identified major price-driving factors in sneaker sales Found brands that charge premium without proportional quality Highlighted sneakers offering the best value for money Provided clear insights to help buyers make data-backed purchase decisions Demonstrated how EDA can solve real-world e-commerce problems Outcome / Business Impact

  • Helps buyers avoid overpriced products
  • Enables smarter purchasing decisions
  • Useful for retailers to optimize pricing strategies
  • Strong real-world EDA portfolio project

Gender = []

for page in range(1, 8):
    print(f"Scraping Page {page}")

    url = f"https://www.amazon.in/s?k=sneakers&page={page}"
    driver.get(url)
    time.sleep(2)

    title_elements = driver.find_elements(By.XPATH,'//h2[contains(@class,"a-size-base-plus")]//span')

    for title in title_elements:
        text = title.text.lower().strip()

        if not text:
            continue

        if re.search(r"\bmen\b|\bmens\b|\bman's\b", text):
            Gender.append("Men")
        elif re.search(r"\bwomen\b|\bwomens\b|\bwoman's\b", text):
            Gender.append("Women")
        elif "unisex" in text:
            Gender.append("Unisex")
        else:
            Gender.append("Unknown")

In[]:
MRP = []

for page in range(1, 8):  
    url = f"https://www.amazon.in/s?k=sneakers&page={page}"
    driver.get(url)
    time.sleep(2)
    
    span_elements = driver.find_elements(By.TAG_NAME, 'span')
    for span in span_elements:
        text = span.text.strip()

        match = re.search(r"M\.R\.P:\s*([\d,]+)", text)

        if match:
            MRP.append(match.group(1))
    
    print(f"Page {page} scraped")

print("Total MRPs extracted:", len(MRP))
print(MRP[:10])

In[52]:
Discount_percent = []

for page in range(1, 8):
    url = f"https://www.amazon.in/s?k=sneakers&page={page}"
    driver.get(url)
    time.sleep(2)
    percent_elements = driver.find_elements(By.CLASS_NAME, 'a-row')

    for percent in percent_elements:
        text = percent.text.strip()

        match = re.search(r"\((\d+)%\s*off\)", text)

        if match:
            discount_percent = match.group(1)
            Discount_percent.append(discount_percent)

print("Total discount percentages extracted:", len(Discount_percent))
print(Discount_percent[:10])

['56', '56', '58', '58', '38', '38', '70', '70', '70', '70']

In[]:
Usage_Type = []

for page in range(1, 8):
    print(f"Scraping Page {page}")

    url = f"https://www.amazon.in/s?k=sneakers&page={page}"
    driver.get(url)
    time.sleep(2)

    title_elements = driver.find_elements(
        By.XPATH, '//h2[contains(@class,"a-size-base-plus")]//span'
    )

    for title in title_elements:
        text = title.text.lower().strip()

        if not text:
            continue

        if re.search(r"\brunning\b|\bjogging\b|\brun\b", text):
            Usage_Type.append("Running")
        elif re.search(r"\bsports\b|\btraining\b|\bgym\b", text):
            Usage_Type.append("Sports")
        elif re.search(r"\bcasual\b|\bsneaker\b|\blifestyle\b|\bdaily\b", text):
            Usage_Type.append("Casual")
        else:
            Usage_Type.append("Unknown")

Hypothesis Testing

Hypothesis Test 1

Is there a significant difference in Selling Price across Price Categories? (ANOVA)

Hypotheses

  • H: Mean Selling Price is same across all Price Categories

  • H: Mean Selling Price differs across Price Categories

In[41]:
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

groups = []
for cat in df['Price_Category'].unique():
    groups.append(df[df['Price_Category'] == cat]['Selling Price'].values)

stat, p_value = f_oneway(*groups)

cl = 0.95
alpha = 1 - cl

if p_value <= alpha:
    print("Reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is relationship between Price Category and Selling Price")
else:
    print("Failed to reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is no relationship between Price Category and Selling Price")

Reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is relationship between Price Category and Selling Price
In[8]:
sns.boxplot(
    x=df['Price_Category'],

)
plt.title('H1: Price Category vs Selling Price')
plt.show()

Conclusion

Reject Null Hypothesis

Selling prices vary significantly across different price categories.

Hypothesis Test 2

Does Rating Category depend on Gender? (Chi-Square Test)

Hypotheses

H (Null Hypothesis): Gender and Rating_Category are independent (no relationship).

H (Alternative Hypothesis): Gender and Rating_Category are dependent (there is a relationship).

In[5]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df['Gender'], df['Rating_Category'])

chi2, p_value, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

cl = 0.95
alpha = 1 - cl

if p_value <= alpha:
    print("Reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is relationship between Gender and Rating Category")
else:
    print("Failed to reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is no relationship between Gender and Rating Category")

Hypothesis Test 3

Does Customer Rating differ between Men and Women? (Independent T-Test)

Hypotheses

H (Null Hypothesis): Mean ratings of Men and Women are the same

H (Alternative Hypothesis): Mean ratings of Men and Women are different

In[7]:
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind


men_ratings = df[df['Gender'] == 'Men']['Rating']
women_ratings = df[df['Gender'] == 'Women']['Rating']


t_stat, p_value = ttest_ind(men_ratings, women_ratings, equal_var=False)

cl = 0.95
alpha = 1 - cl

if p_value <= alpha:
    print("Reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is relationship between Gender and Rating")
else:
    print("Failed to reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is no relationship between Gender and Rating")

t_stat, p_value

Reject Null Hypothesis i.e There is relationship between Gender and Rating

PROJECT CONCLUSION

This project focused on analyzing Amazon sneaker product data to understand pricing behavior, customer perception, and discount strategies using Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) and statistical hypothesis testing.

Exploratory Data Analysis Summary

The dataset contained sneakers across multiple brands, genders, price categories, usage types, and rating categories.

Most products belonged to the Budget and Low-Mid price segments, indicating a strong price-sensitive customer base.

Ratings were largely concentrated between 3.5 to 4.5, showing generally positive customer satisfaction.

Casual usage sneakers dominated the dataset, highlighting higher demand for everyday wear compared to specialized usage.

Univariate Analysis

Univariate analysis was used to understand the individual distribution of sneaker attributes.

The dataset is dominated by mens sneakers, indicating higher availability and demand in this segment.

Most sneakers fall under the Budget and Low-Mid price categories, showing that affordability is a key factor in the sneaker market.

Customer ratings are mostly concentrated between 3.5 and 4.5, reflecting generally good product satisfaction.

Casual and sneaker usage types appear most frequently, highlighting everyday wear as the primary use case.

Insight: The sneaker market strongly targets affordable, well-rated products focused on daily and casual use.

Bivariate Analysis

Bivariate analysis helped identify relationships between sneaker attributes.

Selling prices vary significantly across price categories, confirming that categorization effectively separates sneakers by market segment.

Customer ratings differ across gender, suggesting variations in preferences or perceived comfort and design.

Brand-wise price analysis shows noticeable price dispersion, indicating brand positioning influences sneaker pricing.

Discount amounts do not vary significantly across usage types, implying uniform discount strategies.

Insight: Sneaker pricing and ratings are influenced by category, brand, and gender, while discounting remains largely non-targeted.

Overall Business Takeaways

Pricing and discounting strategies play a key role in customer purchasing behavior.

Gender impacts customer feedback and should be considered for targeted marketing.

Usage type does not influence discounting, suggesting potential scope for differentiated promotional strategies.

Budget-friendly products with good ratings present the strongest value proposition.
